Here are some great resources that explain how tidal coefficients (the measure of tidal range strength) influence fishing success:

📘 Informational Guides

1. TidesToFish – “Tide Coefficient Explained”

  • Defines tidal coefficient as the ratio of daily tidal range to mean spring range (e.g., 70 = moderate) fishingandfish.com+12tidestofish.com+12youtube.com+12.

  • Explains how higher coefficients (50–90) lead to stronger currents, which stimulate fish feeding—but very high (>100) can make fishing tricky tidestofish.com.

2. Anglers Advantage – “Ultimate Guide to the Perfect Tidal Coefficient for Epic Fishing”

  • Explores how tidal coefficient influences fish behavior, bait choice, tide structure, and timing.

  • Offers specific coefficient ranges for locations like Cabo San Lucas and the Great Barrier Reef anglersadvantageguideservice.com+1tides4fishing.com+1.

3. Fishing&Fish – “How Does Tide Affect Fishing?”

  • Breaks down tidal phases—high, low, incoming, outgoing—and the differences between spring and neap tides.

  • Summarizes how spring tides (high coefficients) boost feeding activity (~30% increased success), while neap tides reduce it (~20%) begintofish.com+7fishingandfish.com+7fishreeler.org+7.

🎥 Video Primer

A concise, ~5‑minute YouTube video explaining what tidal coefficient is, why it matters for fishing, and how to use it effectively.

🔍 Quick Takeaways

Tidal PhaseCharacteristicsFishing Prospects
Low coefficient (<50, neap)Minimal tidal movementWeaker currents; fish less active
Moderate (50–90)Moderate currents, enlivened ecosystemsOptimal—water stirs up food, activates fish
High coefficient (>90)Very strong currents, extreme water levelsActive fish—but may be harder to fish safely
Slack tide (around high or low)Water movement pausesMixed impact—can lead to feeding consolidations or inactivity

✅ How to Use This Knowledge

  1. Check tide charts in your area—they list predicted coefficients.

  2. Plan outings around moderate to strong tidal coefficients (50–90).

  3. Choose tide phase based on your location:

    • Incoming tide brings prey inshore—great near reefs and estuaries.

    • Outgoing tide flushes fish from flats and channels—ideal for deeper water anglers.

  4. Match gear and techniques to tidal conditions:

    • Fast currents → heavier rigs/lures.

    • Slow currents → lighter tackle, finesse baits.

how do fish behave during different tidal coefficient?
ChatGPT said:

Fish behavior changes significantly with the tidal coefficient, which measures how strong the tides are based on the difference between high and low tides (range). Here's a breakdown of how fish typically behave across different tidal coefficients:

🔵 Low Tidal Coefficient (0–50) – Neap Tides

Weak tidal movement, slack current

Fish Behavior:

  • Fish tend to be less active, especially predators that rely on currents to hunt.

  • Baitfish may stay dispersed due to lack of current-driven congregation.

  • Feeding windows are short and occur mostly during peak tide changes.

  • Water clarity is higher, making fish spookier—especially in shallows.

Best Strategies:

  • Fish structure or deeper channels, where current still exists.

  • Use finesse presentations, lighter tackle, and stealth.

🟡 Moderate Tidal Coefficient (50–90) – Normal Tides

Balanced water movement, steady current

Fish Behavior:

  • Ideal feeding conditions—enough current to move food but not too much to make fish conserve energy.

  • Predatory fish become active, ambushing bait near current breaks, drop-offs, and estuary mouths.

  • Baitfish group up tighter, attracting larger fish.

Best Strategies:

  • Focus on transition periods (rising/falling tide).

  • Target points, jetties, inlets, and reef edges where current concentrates bait.

  • Use natural or live baits, or lures that work well with moving water (like swimbaits, bucktails, or jerkbaits).

🔴 High Tidal Coefficient (90–120+) – Spring Tides

Strongest tidal movement, heavy current

Fish Behavior:

  • Fish are highly active, especially during incoming and outgoing tides.

  • Aggressive feeding behavior—they capitalize on strong currents to feed heavily.

  • Some species move into shallow areas during higher water access.

  • But: too strong current may push fish into eddies, slack zones, or deeper pockets to conserve energy.

Best Strategies:

  • Be mobile—fish may shift quickly based on water level.

  • Look for current breaks like behind pilings, sandbars, or bends in a channel.

  • Use heavier gear and bigger lures to cope with the water flow.

Summary Table

Tidal CoefficientWater MovementFish ActivityBest Tactic
0–50 (Neap)Very weakLowFish deep & slow
50–90 (Moderate)Balanced currentHighPrime time—fish structure & tide turns
90–120+ (Spring)StrongVery High (briefly)Heavy gear, focus on current breaks

High (90–120+)Hyper-aggressive in first half of tide swing—then harder to fish due to turbulent water.Throw heavy spoons, pencil poppers, or metal lures in fast current areas, like inlet mouths. Hold on tight. Use wire leaders.

✅ Pro Tip:

During spring tides (high coefficients), hit the water early in the incoming tide or late outgoing before the current maxes out. Fish move in to feed aggressively, but often retreat mid-tide when the current rips.

ChatGPT said:

You're almost there! The main issues with your script are:

  1. You have a myFunction() wrapper with doGet() inside it — this is invalid in Apps Script.

  2. doGet() must be at the top level, not inside another function.

  3. You shouldn't use JSON.parse() on parameters that are already strings.

  4. You’re missing a return value at the end of doGet() — it must return a valid ContentService response.

  5. "GOOGLE_SHEET_ADDRESS_GOES_HERE" should be the actual spreadsheet ID, not the full URL.

✅ Fixed and Working Version:

javascript
function doGet(e) {
  // Replace with your actual Spreadsheet ID (not the full URL)
  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.openById("YOUR_SPREADSHEET_ID_HERE").getSheetByName('Sheet1');

  // Get parameters directly (assuming they're passed as URL parameters)
  var fishcaught = e.parameter.fishcaught || '';
  var location = e.parameter.location || '';
  var wind = e.parameter.wind || '';
  var speed = e.parameter.speed || '';
  var water = e.parameter.water || '';
  var tide = e.parameter.tide || '';
  var moon = e.parameter.moon || '';
  var species = e.parameter.species || '';
  var details = e.parameter.details || '';

  var formattedTime = Utilities.formatDate(new Date(), "GMT-5", "h:mm a");
  var formattedDate = Utilities.formatDate(new Date(), "GMT-5", "MM/dd/yyyy");

  // Append data to the sheet
  sheet.appendRow([
    formattedDate,
    formattedTime,
    fishcaught,
    species,
    location,
    wind,
    speed,
    water,
    tide,
    moon,
    details
  ]);

  // Return success response
  return ContentService.createTextOutput("Saved successfully");
}

You said:
Fishers tend to have ideal values for tidal coefficients depending on each location. We know that large coefficients can produce optimal seabed movements for fishing in some places, but perhaps elsewhere they may drag too much algae and dirt, making fishing impractical. how will this effect my fishing?
ChatGPT said:

Great question — tidal coefficient plays a major role in fishing success, but its effects depend heavily on your local environment. Let’s break down how low, medium, and high tidal coefficients may impact your fishing in places like Long Island's North Shore (which you've mentioned before), and what to look for:

🌊 What is a Tidal Coefficient?

  • It’s a number (typically 20–120) that expresses the magnitude of the tidal swing — the difference between high and low tide.

    • High coefficient = stronger tide shifts (more current, more water movement)

    • Low coefficient = weaker tide shifts (less current)

🔍 How It Affects Your Fishing

Tidal CoefficientWater MovementProsConsIn Your Area
Low (20–50)Gentle flowCalm water, finesse baits work, sight fishing possibleLess bait movement, harder to trigger feedingGood for finesse fishing fluke, porgies in coves or flats
Medium (51–85)Balanced tideNatural current, bait is moving, good structure clarityStillness during slack periodsBest for predictable current near rocky points and jetties
High (86–120)Strong currentBig fish feed aggressively near structure, bait flushes in/outToo much flow = muddy water, debris, unfishable near algae bedsRisk of excess weed/algae in tidal creeks, strong sweeps off jetties

📍 Local Application (Long Island North Shore)

  • Inlets, estuaries (e.g., West Harbor, Bayville, Morgan Park):

    • High coefficients can be great for weakfish and stripers feeding on flushed bait — but too high = weeds and mud get stirred up.

    • Watch for outgoing tides after big rain: dirty water, difficult fishing.

  • Beaches, coves, shallow flats:

    • Fish are spooky on low coefficients (calm water) — use light tackle and stealth.

    • Medium coefficients are ideal: enough current to keep bait active, without blowing up the spot.

  • Jetty fishing (e.g., Stehli Beach or Glen Cove Breakwater):

    • High coefficients = potential gold mine for blitzes and aggressive strikes near structure.

    • But be cautious — too much sweep can make lures hard to control.

🎯 How to Use This Info Practically

  1. Check the coefficient before your trip (sites like tides4fishing.com list it for each day).

Do you want dropdowns for things like wind, tide, moon phase, species? Yes I need: # fish caught, species, location, wind, speed, water, tide,coefficient, moon, details, Solunar Theory PS: Read this and see if there are another other dropdowns i should add. Tell me before adding them : Current is the movement of water against itself or a geographic feature. Tides are not currents. They cause currents. Tides are actually very long waves. The Incoming tide is the entire period between low and high tide, and the Outgoing is the time between high and low. The difference in tide height between the two is called the tidal range. Some tides, called "Plus" tides have more range between high and low compared to average, and that means more water moving and stronger currents. Some tides have less range ("minus" tides) and that means less water moving and less current. Slack tide is the undefined time period at peak high and low tide where the water doesn't appear to be moving (even though it always is). The measurement of the actual tide compared to the Mean (average) tide height is called the tide coefficient, which can range from like 30 to 120 or something like that. A coefficient of 35 would be a very weak tide with not much water moving and much less range between high and low tide. A coefficient of 115 would be a very high tide with a much higher volume of water moving and creating very strong currents. A coefficient of 60-70 is about average. The moon phase has strong influence on the tides, and the full moon and new moon will result in the highest tidal coefficient, called the Moon Tides. The midpoint between the moons will be the lowest coefficient. In general, saltwater fish tend to feed the best when the water is moving. The current stirs up things fish eat and disorients schools of baitfish. In general, the stronger the current the better the action. The higher the tidal coefficient the better the fishing should be, emphasis on should. When the tide changes right at sunrise, it's called the breaking tide. That often corresponds full and new moon phases. For many thats the holy grail of trying to time your fishing. If it's also cloudy or a weather event is moving in that's an extra bonus. Some areas produce better on an incoming tide and some better on outgoing. Look for areas where the current will move bait over and past ambush points. As far as inlets go the outgoing is definitely considered to be the best. The warmer water of the bay tends to hold bait well and the outgoing tide flushes it out into the open ocean to waiting fish. That said, it could go the complete opposite too. In general, I strongly prefer outgoing tide, so I always try to start there. Fish when you can fish, but if you are not trying to plan your trips around the tides you're missing opportunities. The factors to pay attention to are: outgoing tide, high total coefficient, new or full moon, incoming weather, breaking tide. The higher the number of those factors fall on a specific day, in my opinion, the better it will be. Submit this directly to the same Google Sheet (FishingLog25')
